# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We can see from the constraints that our solution must be in $$O(nlogn)$$ format so I decided to formulate a set of time in which our answer is also present and using binary search to find the minimum time.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
 - **How guess Time complexity required for question using contraints :-**
Constraints were :- Array of max 10^5 length 
Now imgaine you were fomulating a solution of $$O(n^2)$$ so total time unit taken would be 10^10 and for $$O(nlogn)$$ around 10^6. One thing that you need to know is that in general 10^8 operations take 1 second time and it is usually the time limit of the questions if not given. So for the given question time complexity must be $$O(nlogn)$$ or lower.
 - **How to make the set** 
 We can see that max length and trip is 10^7 so in my solution i took max time to be 10^14 because it won't reach beyond that. Minimum time taken cannot be lower than 1.
 - **Check function**
 It calculate the trips that can be made in particular time and than check if the trips are more or less than required and if conditions are met returns true else false;
 - **Dividing Condition**
 if particular selected time i.e $$mid$$ trips can be made than we store that in answer and search for another answer in lesser time (lower half) as we need to find it in minimum possible time. We we cannot make the trips in that time than we need to search in upper half. 
# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(NlogK)$$
where N is the length of the array and K is 10^14
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:$$O(1)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

