solutions.content:
A intuition is that a tire will never be used for too many laps.  Since r >= 2,  2^30 is already a very large number. So let's say, a tire will be used for 30 laps at most.

Let best[i] = the minimal cost to run i laps.
We can initialize f[i] by using only a single tire. 
For example, 
use tire 0 for 1 laps: update best[1] with f0
use tire 0 for 2 laps, update best[2] with f0 * r0
...
use tire 1 for 1 laps, update best[1] with f1
use tire 2 for 2 laps, update best[2] with f1 * r1
...

Now, the goal is to calculate all best[x]  from 1 to numberLaps.

Since the last tire can be used for 1 ~30 laps, we can iterate all the possibilities of best[x]:
The last tire run 1 lap: update best[x] with best[1] + best[x-1] + change
The last tire run 2 laps: update best[x] with best[2] + best[x-2] + change
...

code:

```
class Solution {
public:
    long long M = pow(10, 6);
    int minimumFinishTime(vector<vector<int>>& tires, int change, int laps) {
        vector<long long> best = vector<long long> (2000, pow(10, 10));
        best[0] = 0;
        for (auto t: tires) {
            long long cur = t[0];
            long long last = 0;
            for (int d = 1; d <= 30; d++ ) {
                best[d] = min(best[d], last + cur);
                last = last + cur;
                cur *= t[1];
                if (cur > M) break;
            }    
        }
        for (long long d = 1; d <= laps; d++) {
            for (long long l = min(d, (long long)30); l >= 1; l --) {
                best[d] = min(best[d], best[l] + best[d - l] + change);
            }
        }
        return best[laps];
    }
};
```

