It is a difficuit problem but may be the easiest to understand in recent contests. 
Before any brain work, we can translate the description of the problem as follows:
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minimumFinishTime(vector<vector<int>>& tires, int ct, int l) {
		// states: current tire - id,
		//         laps on this tire - idl, 
		//         tire param - idp;
        // repeat for each lap: 
        //     change tire:  time = time + ct + tiretime(id_new,0,idp_new);
        //     don't change: time = time + tiretime(id,idl+1,idp);
		//
		//            dp table filling order
		//       dp          lap1  lap2  lap3  lap4  ...
		// no tire switch      ↘ 	 ↘ 	   ↘ 	 ↘
		//  tire switch1       ↘ 	 ↘ 	   ↘ 	 ↘
		//  tire switch2       ↘ 	 ↘ 	   ↘ 	 ↘
		//       ...
		}
```
Look at the option of change tire and don't change tire, it matches the dynamic programming pattern. We can go through from lap 0 to lap N, adding the time at each lap and keeps the minimum time at each lap. (Are these patterns remind you of some other problems?) If we have limited tire switching, this method could work. However, if we switch tires at each lap, It takes as many as `tiresize * numLaps` for all tire combinations. Following the description is the easiest way to implement but always fails in medium/hard problem. 

Luckily, The time taken on the same tire is very predictable if we know the laps, and we do not need to calculate for each lap. We now can change or options as follow:
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minimumFinishTime(vector<vector<int>>& tires, int ct, int l) {
		// states: current tire - id,
		//         laps on this tire - idl, 
		//         tire param - idp;
        // start with l laps, repeat until there is no laps:
		//    take k laps: 
        //        use the same tire for k laps: time = time +  tiretime(id,k,idp) + ct;
		//        where tiretime(id,k,idp) = sumofk(id*idp^(k-1));
		}
```

Our choice now is for how many laps we use the same tire. The dynamic programming pattern has changed. Now with a single parameter lap l, our dp[l] represents the minimum cost regardless of how many tires switched. Well it is still dynamic programming because we can use data from dp[1..l-1] to derive dp[l]. This updating rule becomes:

```
time = INT_MAX
for k in [1,l-1]:
	time = min(time, dp[k] + ct + dp[l-k])
// for no tire switching
time = min(time, min_time_noswitch(tire,l));
```

With the help of dynamic programming, we have stripped the problem down to a `min_time_noswitch` function. Therefore, the last step is to calculate the minimum timecost when there is no tire switching. 
This is a calculation process done before the dynamic programming loop. Note we only need to calculate untill the `ct + tire[i][0]` because the tire timecost increases exponentially, and it becomes necessary to switch tires beyond certain cost level. 

The overall code is shown below:
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minimumFinishTime(vector<vector<int>>& tire, int ct, int l) {
        long long dp[1001] = {0};
        // no tire switching
        map<int,long long> mp; // pair: numLaps, min time cost to complete lap without tire switching
        for(int j = 1; j <= l; j++) mp[j] = LLONG_MAX;
        for(int i = 0; i < tire.size(); i++) { // only count up to (ct + tire[i][0])
            long long tm = tire[i][0];
            long long totm = 0;
            int param = tire[i][1];
            for(int j = 1; j <= l; j++) {
                if(tm <= ct + tire[i][0]) {
                    totm += tm;
                    mp[j] = min(mp[j], totm);
                    tm = tm * param;
                }
                else break;
            }
        }

        long long time = checktime(ct, l, dp, mp);

        return time;
    }

    long long checktime(int ct, int k, long long dp[1001], map<int,long long> & mp) {
        if(dp[k] != 0) return dp[k];
        long long mt = LLONG_MAX;
        for(int i = 1; i <= k/2; i++) {
            mt = min(mt, checktime(ct, i, dp, mp) + checktime(ct, k-i, dp, mp) + ct);
        }
        if(mp.find(k) != mp.end()) mt = min(mt, mp[k]);

        dp[k] = mt;
        return mt;
    }
};
```

