# Intuition
At my first glance, this problem involves **exponentiation** (<code>fi * ri<sup>(x-1)</sup></code>), moreover, the minimum value for `ri` is `2`, which means the result may grow dramatically fast *(fact #1)*. However, there is no **"modulo <code>10<sup>9</sup> + 7</code>"** in the description, which suggests the result may not outgrow max safe integers for most programming language *(fact 2)*.
Even though this observation can easily be proved formally, isn't it a great step to move forward? As now we have **2 clues for the price of one**, we can take advantage of these facts.

# Approach
Let's define an array `dp`, in which `dp[i]` represents the minimum time to finish `i+1` laps *(the `+1` is to save 4 bytes of memory, what have I done to myself ;-; )*.

## Step 1: Find a heuristic upper bound for all dp[i]
Let's completely ignore the "combo boost" when using the same tire in multiple lap. Suppose we change tire every single lap, then of course, we would **always** choose the tire with the **least f[i]**. Therefore, our upper bound would simply be: $$dp[i] = min(f[*]) * (i+1) + changeTime * i$$, or in the code:
```js
  const dp = Array(numLaps).fill(0);

  dp[0] = 1e9;
  for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) dp[0] = Math.min(dp[0], tires[i][0])

  let minInc = dp[0] + changeTime;
  for (let i = 1; i < numLaps; i++) dp[i] = dp[i - 1] + minInc;
```
It's a bit different for optimization purpose, but the overall ideas remain.
After this step, we have also proved that the answer would not exceed $$10^9$$ as there always exists at least one solution that is lower than that threshold.
Another nice observation is by this strategy, the min addition time it takes to finish 1 more lap is `minInc = min(f[*]) + changeTime`

## Step 2: Try optimizing dp by using the same tire in multiple successive lap
Try using each tire multiple times.
We only interested in the additional time for every one new lap, which is, given in the description, <code>fi * ri<sup>(x-1)</sup></code>.
Notice that this additional time would keep increasing everytime a new lap is added. When it **surpasses the `minInc`**, there is no point to continue adding more laps as we can just change tire to get better result. 
How long for an additional time to surpass `minInc`, in average? It's simply $$log_r(minInc / f)$$. We only have to keep in mind that this step only requires logarithmic time for each tire.
The code:
```jsx
  for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    let inc = tires[i][0];
    let sum = inc;

    for (let k = 1; k < numLaps; k++) {
      inc *= tires[i][1];
      if (inc >= minInc) break;

      sum += inc;  
      if (sum < dp[k]) {
        dp[k] = sum;
        maxK = Math.max(maxK, k);
      }
    }
  }
```
Now, we introduced a new variable `maxK` to indicate the longest successive lap can be optimally done using a single tire.

## Step 3: Finding optimal DP
In the step 2, we have only handled the case in which we are only using 1 tire. We will now allow changing tires!
To evaluate `dp[i]`, assuming every `dp[j]` with $$0 <= j < i$$ is **optimal**, if we try changing tire after finishing `j+1` laps, the optimal time for this strategy would be $$dp[j] + dp[i-j-1] + changeTime$$.
Note that we don't have to iterate `j`'s that are below `i - maxK - 1`. As the maximum number of successive laps is `maxK`, if `j < i - maxK - 1`, then there exists `x > j`, so that we can try changing tire at `x` and still get the optimal result.
The code:
```jsx
  for (let i = 1; i < numLaps; i++) {
    for (let j = Math.max(0, i - maxK - 1); j < i; j++) {
      dp[i] = Math.min(dp[i], dp[j] + dp[i - j - 1] + changeTime)
    }
  }
```

# Complexity
- let `m = min(f[i])`
- Time complexity: $$O(n*log(changeTime + m))$$
- Space complexity: $$O(numLaps)$$

# Code
```jsx
/**
 * @param {number[][]} tires
 * @param {number} changeTime
 * @param {number} numLaps
 * @return {number}
 */
var minimumFinishTime = function(tires, changeTime, numLaps) {
  const n = tires.length;
  const dp = Array(numLaps).fill(0);

  dp[0] = 1e9;
  for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) dp[0] = Math.min(dp[0], tires[i][0])

  let minInc = dp[0] + changeTime;
  for (let i = 1; i < numLaps; i++) dp[i] = dp[i - 1] + minInc;
  let maxK = 0;

  for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    let inc = tires[i][0];
    let sum = inc;

    for (let k = 1; k < numLaps; k++) {
      inc *= tires[i][1];
      if (inc >= minInc) break;

      sum += inc;  
      if (sum < dp[k]) {
        dp[k] = sum;
        maxK = Math.max(maxK, k);
      }
    }
  }

  for (let i = 1; i < numLaps; i++) {
    for (let j = Math.max(0, i - maxK - 1); j < i; j++) {
      dp[i] = Math.min(dp[i], dp[j] + dp[i - j - 1] + changeTime)
    }
  }

  return dp[numLaps - 1];
};
```

