# Approach
For a given number of laps `m`, the required time can be found as the minimum of either:
- The time needed using only the best available tire for that number of laps
- The minimum sum of time required for the two lap numbers `a` and `b` with `a + b == m`, plus one `change_time` 

With this approach, iterative dynamic programming can be easily implemented.

Special care must be taken when calculating the time needed using only one tire. As the exponentially growing time can lead to integer overflow, the exponentiation must be stopped early enough. It can be stopped as soon as the average time of that tire per lap surpasses the upper bound for what the worst possible tire can achieve when changed after every lap ($10^5 \text{ s per lap} + 10^5 \text{ s change time}$).

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
  - $O(\text{tires.len()} * \text{num\_laps} + \text{num\_laps}^2)$ (worst case with many `r_i == 1`)
  - $O(\text{tires.len()} + \text{num\_laps}^2)$ (average case, most `r_i > 1`)

- Space complexity:
$O(\text{num\_laps})$ additional space

# Code
```
impl Solution {
    pub fn minimum_finish_time(tires: Vec<Vec<i32>>, change_time: i32, num_laps: i32) -> i32 {
        let num_laps = num_laps as usize;

        let mut dp = vec![1000000000; num_laps + 1]; //dp[i] = fastest time to complete i laps
        dp[0] = 0;

        for tire in tires.iter() {
            //for each tire, calculate the time to finish [0, num_laps] laps without changing tires
            //and find the best value for every number of laps
            let mut time: i64 = 0;
            let mut r: i64 = 1;
            for lap in 1..(num_laps + 1) {
                time += tire[0] as i64 * r;
                if time > 200000 * (1 + lap as i64) {
                    //changing tires is faster in any case
                    break;
                }
                dp[lap] = std::cmp::min(dp[lap], time as i32);
                r *= tire[1] as i64;
            }
        }

        for laps in 2..(num_laps + 1) {
            let mut best_time = dp[laps];
            for x in 1..(laps) {
                //change tire after x laps
                best_time = std::cmp::min(best_time, dp[x] + dp[laps - x] + change_time);
            }
            dp[laps] = best_time;
        }

        dp[num_laps]
    }

}
```

