# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
$$f[i]$$ the minimum time that finish i laps
Assume at the j lap, we change the tire, j + 1, j + 2, ... i lap, we use the same tire.
In this way, we will get the state transition.
$$f[i] = \underset{j < i}min \{f[j] + \underset{k}min\{cost(k, i - j)\}\} + changeTime$$

$$cost(k, i - j)$$ the total time that we use the same tire for i - j laps
for this term, if the duration of using this tire to run one lap is longer than using the new tire same as the old one plus change tire time, why not we change a new tire whose type is same as the old one?
$$f * r^{x-1} < changeTime + f$$
According to the range of input, we could approximately calculate the upper bound of x. $$x\approx 18$$

The answer is $$f[numLaps]-changeTime$$
Because we could begin the game with any tires.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O((n + numLaps)logT_{max})$$
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n + logT_{max})$$
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minimumFinishTime(vector<vector<int>>& tires, int changeTime, int numLaps) {
        vector<int> best(18, INT_MAX);  
        int n = tires.size();
        int maxdiff = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            long time = tires[i][0], lap = tires[i][0];
            for (int j = 1; lap < changeTime + tires[i][0]; ++j) {
                best[j] = min(best[j], static_cast<int>(time));
                lap *= tires[i][1];
                time += lap;
                maxdiff = max(maxdiff, j);
            }
        }

        vector<int> f(numLaps + 1, INT_MAX);
        f[0] = 0;
        for (int i = 1; i <= numLaps; ++i) {
            for (int j = i - 1; j >= 0 && i - j <= maxdiff; --j) {
                f[i] = min(f[i], f[j] + changeTime + best[i - j]);
            }
        } 
        return f[numLaps] - changeTime;
    }
};
```

