# Intuition
Get a min minutes for laps using lap times less than(changeTime + min(f)) 
Because if fr^n> changeTime+ min_f we can ignore them.

<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
use dp for calculating min time for lap n dp[n] = dp[k]+ dp[n-k] 
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(min(noOfLaps,noOFtires))
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:O(noOFLaps) 
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int minimumFinishTime(int[][] tires, int changeTime, int numLaps) {
        int min  = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        HashMap<Integer,Integer> map = new HashMap<>(); 
        map.put(0,0);
        for(int[] i : tires)min = Math.min(min,i[0]);
        for(int[] i : tires){
            int v = i[0];
            int id = 1;
            int r = i[1];
            int prev =0;
            while(v<min+changeTime){
                map.put(id,Math.min(map.getOrDefault(id,Integer.MAX_VALUE),v+prev));
                id++;
                prev +=v;
                v=v*r;
            }
        }
        map.put(0,0);
        int k = map.size()-1;
        int [] dp = new int[numLaps+1];
        Arrays.fill(dp,Integer.MAX_VALUE);
        for(int i =1;i<dp.length;i++){
            if(map.containsKey(i)) dp[i] = map.get(i);
            for(int j =i-1;j>0 && j>=i-k;j--){
                dp[i] = Math.min(dp[i],changeTime+dp[j]+map.get(i-j));
            }
        }
        return dp[numLaps];
    }
}
```

