solutions.content:
I couldn't get it under during the contest, but I took some time to think and came back with some optimizations and finally got it. I later read that you can just pre-compute the no-tire-change times up to lap 17 and not worry about dynamically figuring out when to stop, but this is faster and anyways, I worked really hard on this, so I am posting it, even though keeping track dynamically makes it more complicated! I also included the slower, hard-coded, max depth of 17 version down below.

Edit: rh137, my source for the hardcoding idea, pointed out that the cutoff needs to be higher than 16, my original cut-off. 17 appears to work!

```
class Solution {
    func minimumFinishTime(_ tires: [[Int]], _ changeTime: Int, _ numLaps: Int) -> Int {
        //the maxProductiveDepth will represent the max number of laps, j, over the (r_i, f_i) pairs such that, looking at the total time t(j) after lap j 
        // t(x_{j+1}) - t(x_{j}) < f + changeTime
        // because at that point, you are better off changing your tires instead of doing another lap! Another way of saying the same thing is that you should stop calculating individual lap times once the lap time is greater than just changing your tires and doing a lap with fresh ones
        var maxProductiveDepth = 1
        let f_0 = tires[0][0]

        //array to store the best total times over all of the (r,f) pairs if you never changed tires
        //the length will always be equal to maxProductiveDepth
        var bestTotalTimesWithoutChangingTires: [Int] = [0, f_0]

        //loop to calculate the best times over each (r_i, f_i) pair if you never changed tires
        for f_r in tires {
            let f = f_r[0]
            let r  = f_r[1]

            //once the difference between successive laps is greater than the time to do a single lap and change a tire, we will stop calculating
            let max = bestTotalTimesWithoutChangingTires[1] + changeTime

            var power = 1
            var totalTime = 0
            for i in 1...numLaps {
                guard f*power < max else {break}
                totalTime = totalTime + f*power

                //update the array with the best time
                if maxProductiveDepth < i {
                    bestTotalTimesWithoutChangingTires.append(totalTime)
                    maxProductiveDepth = i
                } else if totalTime < bestTotalTimesWithoutChangingTires[i] {
                    bestTotalTimesWithoutChangingTires[i] = totalTime
                }
                power *= r
            }
        }

        //dynamic programming array to store the fastest possible time to complete a given number of laps
        var raceTime = Array(repeating: 0, count: numLaps + 1)

        //fill up the dynamic programming array
        for i in 1...numLaps {
            //only bother checking the time if you never switched tires in cases where that would actually be a good idea - i.e. there is an (r,f) pair where the differences in lap times is still less that r + changeTime
            //if you are interested in why we never need to check for non-changing times beyond 17, see rh137's explanation here:
            //https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-time-to-finish-the-race/discuss/1802444/C%2B%2B-Linear-time-DP-with-explanation
            var best = (i < 17 && i <= maxProductiveDepth ? bestTotalTimesWithoutChangingTires[i] : Int.max)

            //pretty stardard dp here - do what you did to finish the first i laps, change tires, then do what you did for the first i-j laps
            for j in 1..<min(17, i/2 + 1) {
                let newTime = raceTime[j] + changeTime + raceTime[i - j]
                if newTime < best {
                    best = newTime
                }
            }
            raceTime[i] = best
        }

        //return the fastest possible time to complete numLaps
        return raceTime[numLaps]
    }
}
```


