# Intuition
Not gonna lie, I had a hard time understanding the subject, maybe because it's late in the evening.
Anyways, they ask you to count everytime a number stands in front of **key**, the number which occurred the most times immediately after **key** is the answer.

# Approach
I started by doing a map storing nums[i] and storing and/or incrementing its count (I.e. how many times it occurred after **key**).
As I'm storing/incrementing it, I'm also checking if its count is already bigger than the last biggest count, if so i redeclare my return int *ret*. This way you won't need to iterate over *map*.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(n).

# Code
```
#include <map>
#include <iostream>

class Solution {
public:


    int mostFrequent(vector<int>& nums, int key) {
        std::unordered_map<int,int> map;
        int ret, count = 0;
        for(int i = 0; i < nums.size() - 1; i++)
        {
            if (nums[i] == key)
            {
                map[nums[i + 1]]++;
                if (map[nums[i + 1]] > count)
                {
                    count = map[nums[i + 1]];
                    ret = nums[i + 1];
                }
            }
        }
        return ret;
    }
};
```

